Bitcoin is the most popular form of cryptocurrency, which was first introduced to the world in January, 2009, basically as a digital currency that works by the concept set out in a whitepaper. One of its major attributes is that it is not controlled by a central body authority such as any government issued currency, and has a very low transactional fees than other payment methods online. Bitcoin is a replacement to physical modes of currency, and balances are kept on public ledgers that can be accessed transparently. Bitcoin works regardless of a bank or government backing it and a lot of computing power and networking is used to verify the transactions performed using bitcoins. How does Bitcoin work?
